Anonymous Tue 25 Apr 2023 13:10:57 No.56029254 Report
Quoted By: >>56029302 >>56029493
>>56023606
It's a Ukraine meme. The blocks are explosive reactive armor tiles. Think of them as a layer of explosive sandwiched between two plates. They bolt them onto things like tanks. When certain kinds of armor piercing projectiles strike them, they detonate and push the outer steel plate against the projectile at an angle, which can reduce its penetration and protect the vehicle. Lots of Soviet-era tanks were designed for them. There are pictures of Ukrainians putting them on Western tanks, which were not designed for them--doesn't make it impossible or nonfunctional, just more labor intensive and awkward, and weird looking if you're used to the appearance the vehicles had prior. It has become a meme to show cheerful Ukrainians who have bolted ERA tiles onto stuff while the original owner looks on in disapproval.

>they detonate and push the outer steel plate against the projectile at an angle, which can reduce its penetration and protect the vehicle
If this were true, they'd just mount extra plates. No, ERA is effective against shaped charge projectiles. Those are the ones that use an explosive charge to form and project a stream of copper which penetrates the armor. The explosion of the ERA negates the explosion of the projectile and fucks up its copper stream, and thus its penetrative potential.

Some of the newest Russian stuff like "Relikt" and "Monolit" is claimed to be able to cause an incoming sabot round to tip sideways and hit at an angle, which reduces its penetration somewhat. It ain't magic. The incoming round has to hit at the angle it was designed for, and the ERA tile has to detonate at the proper instant and not a ten thousandth of a second late.

https://youtu.be/mzZaI_eppQw

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reactive_armour#Explosive_reactive_armour

This stuff has been used in combat and the general belief seems to be that it is useful enough to be worth the money and the added weight. Russia exported quite a bit of it to places like India before the war. The Israelis use it too on certain vehicles, manufactured locally, not bought from the Russians.

Anonymous Tue 25 Apr 2023 16:31:43 No.56032429 Report
Quoted By: >>56032786 >>56035244
>>56032090
>The love is there to want to draw and get better
No, it's not.
If you wanted to draw, you would be drawing whenever you had the chance.
If you wanted to get better, you would be happy to draw badly because that would let you find where you need to improve.

Instead, you are defeating yourself on approach. You're attributing it to "confidence," but that's bullshit because only a confident and experienced man is in a position to accurately judge if "[he doesn't] know if [he] can do that." Really it's because you know that after your try your result will not be what you wanted and then you will feel like you wasted the time.

That's loss aversion.

Change your goal. Make a completed exercise your goal, like a cubes floating in space exercise, or a shading on a sphere exercise. Something simple, stupid, and that you don't care about. That way, you're not invested in the result and if it comes up short it feels like practice instead of like failure.

The art you want to create is a BYPRODUCT. Nobody who wants to go to the moon gets there by trying to jump really fucking high. But the nerds who get boners by studying the math that describes trajectories in gravitational fields can hit that pebble with a bottle rocket on a Florida beach.

>>56034818
Not any of these anons, but here’s my mild take.

Study if you want to get better faster, but approach it like you would learning anything else.

1. Figure out what you want to learn.
2. Gather resources, videos, books and get the info first with active reading/watching and taking notes.
3. Practice whatever skill this is, thinking about what you’re doing, say copying the figures from a book or something.
4. Reflect on your practice.
5. Sleep on what you’ve learned (and getting sleep is really important for learning and moving info from short term to long term.)
6. Apply what you’ve learned, testing yourself.

Studies are to be done separately and can be considered in a similar method, drawing from life is best.

If you can’t get up the will to do that, it is not impossible to improve in other ways, though the fundamentals can only be ignored for so long. Turn your fun drawing into practice and learning. “I want to draw a fat ass, so let me focus on the ass muscle anatomy in this drawing of my waifur.”

I believe anyone can draw but motivation is weak, horniness is weak, depression can be strong. The idea is discipline. Drawing something is always better than nothing, and discipline is a muscle that needs to be developed.

That’s just my two cents.
